00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:53.895
If m is an integer is m odd?

00:03:58.690 --> 00:04:08.550
Statement number one: m divided
by 2 not-- they write

00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:12.250
it real big and bold--
not even integer.

00:04:16.079 --> 00:04:18.790
Well, that doesn't
tell me much.

00:04:18.790 --> 00:04:21.120
I mean that doesn't tell
me that this is odd.

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:24.510
In fact, it's not an even
integer but if this was an odd

00:04:24.510 --> 00:04:27.470
integer then that means that m
is an even integer, right?

00:04:27.470 --> 00:04:32.550
Anything that's divisible by 2
and results in an integer--

00:04:32.550 --> 00:04:34.820
right, that's essentially saying
that it's divisible by

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:37.150
2-- by definition is
going to be even.

00:04:37.150 --> 00:04:40.400
So for example, what
if m divided by 2

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:41.590
is equal to 3, right?

00:04:41.590 --> 00:04:46.900
3 is not an even integer but
still m would equal 6.

00:04:46.900 --> 00:04:50.130
And then m would be even.

00:04:50.130 --> 00:04:52.480
And I mean they're not
telling us much here.

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:57.210
m divided by 2 could be equal
to 2.5 in which case m would

00:04:57.210 --> 00:04:58.850
be equal to 5 so that would
be an odd integer.

00:04:58.850 --> 00:05:02.000
So this by itself doesn't give
me much information.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.480
Statement number two: m minus
3 is an even integer.

00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:13.710
Well, this is useful, right?

00:05:13.710 --> 00:05:20.150
If you subtract an odd number
from a number and you get an

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:24.310
even number, this number
is going to be even.

00:05:24.310 --> 00:05:25.600
And let's think about that.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:27.470
If I have an even number--
let me just

00:05:27.470 --> 00:05:29.800
write a bunch of numbers.

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:33.410
Let me write x, y, and z.

00:05:33.410 --> 00:05:35.600
And let's say they're
consecutive, right?

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:37.530
Actually let me write
it even better.

00:05:37.530 --> 00:05:46.720
Let's say that x is even--
let's say x is odd.

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:48.450
Then x plus 1 is going
to be what?

00:05:48.450 --> 00:05:49.880
It's going to be even, right?

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:51.390
The next number will be even.

00:05:51.390 --> 00:05:55.650
Then x plus 2 is going
to be odd.

00:05:55.650 --> 00:06:02.520
And then x plus 3 is
going to be even.

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:04.450
And then if you go the other
way-- actually I should have

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:09.060
gone to the way first-- x
minus 1 would be even.

00:06:09.060 --> 00:06:11.650
x minus 2 would be odd.

00:06:11.650 --> 00:06:15.020
And x minus 3 would
be even, right?

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:21.170
If you have an odd number and
you subtract out an odd number

00:06:21.170 --> 00:06:23.210
and you get an even number
then this number

00:06:23.210 --> 00:06:24.910
is going to be odd.

00:06:24.910 --> 00:06:27.960
So this statement two by itself
is actually sufficient.

00:06:27.960 --> 00:06:29.620
And play around with some
numbers if that intuition

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:30.900
doesn't make sense.

00:06:30.900 --> 00:06:34.540
Statement two, by itself, is
sufficient to solve this

00:06:34.540 --> 00:06:37.360
problem and you don't need
statement one at all.

